Image pull secrets.

If your pod runs an image from a private registry, the kube-let on the node needs credentials to pull it. That is what image pull secrets are for.

Step one, create the credential as a secret. You run kubectl create secret docker registry, giving it the docker server, a username, and a password. That creates a secret of type docker config jason, whose data is a base sixty-four of a docker config file.

Step two, reference it from the pod spec. You add an image pull secrets field, naming your secret, alongside the container that uses the private image. That is it. The kube-let uses the secret to authenticate when pulling the image. And crucially, the secret is only used for image pull. The running container never sees it as an environment variable or a file.

Now, a cluster wide alternative. If every pod in a namespace needs the same registry credential, you can set it once on the namespace's default service account, and skip the per pod field. You patch the default service account to include the image pull secret. From then on, every pod created in that namespace that does not override its service account picks up the credential automatically. Service accounts land properly in notebook ten.

On our map, this is the one section that reaches up out of the config box, to the registry. Specifically, the image pull secret chip. Because pulling a private image is exactly where config meets the registry.
